59:45.000 --> 59:48.000
The next element of the system

59:48.000 --> 59:51.000
is the planning of the training.

59:51.000 --> 59:54.000
We need to understand who, how and when we will be teaching.

59:54.000 --> 59:57.000
The next step is to develop the program

59:57.000 --> 01:00:00.000
and how we will develop the competence.

01:00:00.000 --> 01:00:03.000
The next step is to develop the training.

01:00:03.000 --> 01:00:06.000
The next step is to assess the effectiveness.

01:00:06.000 --> 01:00:09.000
The assessment of the effectiveness

01:00:09.000 --> 01:00:12.000
is the final element of the system.

01:00:12.000 --> 01:00:15.000
Let's recall the methods

01:00:15.000 --> 01:00:18.000
for assessing the effectiveness of the training.

01:00:18.000 --> 01:00:21.000
When we talk about the assessment of the effectiveness

01:00:21.000 --> 01:00:24.000
we often mention the name

01:00:24.000 --> 01:00:27.000
of Donald Kirkpatrick

01:00:27.000 --> 01:00:30.000
who 30 years ago proposed

01:00:30.000 --> 01:00:33.000
the technology of assessing the effectiveness of the training.

01:00:33.000 --> 01:00:36.000
Now we know it as the Kirkpatrick model

01:00:36.000 --> 01:00:39.000
or the 4-level model.

01:00:39.000 --> 01:00:42.000
What is its essence?

01:00:42.000 --> 01:00:45.000
Let's recall.

01:00:45.000 --> 01:00:48.000
When we talk about the assessment of the effectiveness

01:00:48.000 --> 01:00:51.000
of the training or some training program

01:00:51.000 --> 01:00:54.000
we should ask ourselves what we assess.

01:00:54.000 --> 01:00:57.000
Do we assess the training

01:00:57.000 --> 01:01:00.000
which lasted for 16 hours?

01:01:00.000 --> 01:01:03.000
Or do we assess the coach

01:01:03.000 --> 01:01:06.000
or the participants?

01:01:06.000 --> 01:01:09.000
We always ask this question.

01:01:09.000 --> 01:01:12.000
Our task is not to assess the program

01:01:12.000 --> 01:01:15.000
but to assess the changes

01:01:15.000 --> 01:01:18.000
that the training has brought.

01:01:18.000 --> 01:01:21.000
The changes in the work of the participants

01:01:21.000 --> 01:01:24.000
should have led to the goal

01:01:24.000 --> 01:01:27.000
for which the training program was conceived.

01:01:27.000 --> 01:01:30.000
Kirkpatrick proposed to do the following.

01:01:30.000 --> 01:01:33.000
First, he said

01:01:33.000 --> 01:01:36.000
to assess the reaction of the students

01:01:36.000 --> 01:01:39.000
i.e. emotions.

01:01:39.000 --> 01:01:42.000
After the seminar, let's ask

01:01:42.000 --> 01:01:45.000
how the participants felt.

01:01:45.000 --> 01:01:48.000
Did they like the program?

01:01:48.000 --> 01:01:51.000
Did they feel the heat?

01:01:51.000 --> 01:01:54.000
Did they feel cold?

01:01:54.000 --> 01:01:57.000
Did they have a proper lunch?

01:01:57.000 --> 01:02:00.000
This is an assessment of emotions.

01:02:00.000 --> 01:02:03.000
Let's take a look at the sports.

01:02:03.000 --> 01:02:06.000
We can listen to a lecture

01:02:06.000 --> 01:02:09.000
of a great football coach

01:02:09.000 --> 01:02:12.000
and we can say that it was great.

01:02:12.000 --> 01:02:15.000
We spent 2-3 hours with such a positive feeling.

01:02:15.000 --> 01:02:18.000
We say that it was great.

01:02:18.000 --> 01:02:21.000
It is an emotion.

01:02:21.000 --> 01:02:24.000
We need to understand

01:02:24.000 --> 01:02:27.000
what is left in the participants' heads.

01:02:27.000 --> 01:02:30.000
We remember our football lecture.

01:02:30.000 --> 01:02:33.000
Do we remember the main rules?

01:02:33.000 --> 01:02:36.000
Or is there some inner feeling

01:02:36.000 --> 01:02:39.000
about a well-spent time?

01:02:39.000 --> 01:02:42.000
If the football lecture can be like this,

01:02:42.000 --> 01:02:45.000
it should not be like this.

01:02:45.000 --> 01:02:48.000
Our next task is to understand

01:02:48.000 --> 01:02:51.000
what knowledge is left in the participants' heads.

01:02:51.000 --> 01:02:54.000
If we taught operators of the call center

01:02:54.000 --> 01:02:57.000
to work effectively, we need to understand

01:02:57.000 --> 01:03:00.000
that they liked everything.

01:03:00.000 --> 01:03:03.000
They left with the feeling

01:03:03.000 --> 01:03:06.000
that they had a great time.

01:03:06.000 --> 01:03:09.000
This was not the goal.

01:03:09.000 --> 01:03:12.000
The next level is that there is not enough knowledge.

01:03:12.000 --> 01:03:15.000
We can play football,

01:03:15.000 --> 01:03:18.000
but none of us will ever go out on the pitch.

01:03:18.000 --> 01:03:21.000
We can work with objections.

01:03:21.000 --> 01:03:24.000
A manager can sigh a lot

01:03:24.000 --> 01:03:27.000
and say that he has been through a lot of trainings

01:03:27.000 --> 01:03:30.000
and he will go back to the same place.

01:03:30.000 --> 01:03:33.000
But knowledge does not always imply skill.

01:03:33.000 --> 01:03:36.000
We know how to do it.

01:03:36.000 --> 01:03:39.000
We can work with people.

01:03:39.000 --> 01:03:42.000
The next level is the level of behavior.

01:03:42.000 --> 01:03:45.000
How much behavior has changed

01:03:45.000 --> 01:03:48.000
after the training.

01:03:48.000 --> 01:03:51.000
What is behavior? It is competence.

01:03:51.000 --> 01:03:54.000
We understand that this is the most fixed change

01:03:54.000 --> 01:03:57.000
in the development of competence

01:03:57.000 --> 01:04:00.000
that we can analyze.

01:04:00.000 --> 01:04:03.000
Has there been a change?

01:04:03.000 --> 01:04:06.000
No.

01:04:06.000 --> 01:04:09.000
It is easier for those companies

01:04:09.000 --> 01:04:12.000
that have competence models

01:04:12.000 --> 01:04:15.000
to reach the third level of efficiency.

01:04:15.000 --> 01:04:18.000
We have all the tools.

01:04:18.000 --> 01:04:21.000
We developed, we conducted

01:04:21.000 --> 01:04:24.000
assessment centers, we evaluated, we looked.

01:04:24.000 --> 01:04:27.000
We saw what was at the entrance.

01:04:27.000 --> 01:04:30.000
After repeating the procedures,

01:04:30.000 --> 01:04:33.000
we can analyze if there are any changes.

01:04:33.000 --> 01:04:36.000
Can we make changes to the training program

01:04:36.000 --> 01:04:39.000
that we conducted?

01:04:39.000 --> 01:04:42.000
The next point is

01:04:42.000 --> 01:04:45.000
how the fourth level of efficiency

01:04:45.000 --> 01:04:48.000
and the business results

01:04:48.000 --> 01:04:51.000
led to new behavior.

01:04:51.000 --> 01:04:54.000
The operators of our call center

01:04:54.000 --> 01:04:57.000
that we trained and liked

01:04:57.000 --> 01:05:00.000
started to serve the client better.

01:05:00.000 --> 01:05:03.000
What did it lead to?

01:05:03.000 --> 01:05:06.000
It led to more clients.

01:05:06.000 --> 01:05:09.000
Clients became more satisfied with our call center.

01:05:09.000 --> 01:05:12.000
This is a business result

01:05:12.000 --> 01:05:15.000
that we record and that is a consequence

01:05:15.000 --> 01:05:18.000
of competence development.

01:05:18.000 --> 01:05:21.000
To conclude the topic of competence use

01:05:21.000 --> 01:05:24.000
in the development of staff,

01:05:24.000 --> 01:05:27.000
the company receives the competence

01:05:27.000 --> 01:05:30.000
from the employees.

01:05:30.000 --> 01:05:33.000
In those companies where the staff

01:05:33.000 --> 01:05:36.000
uses competence to form the system

01:05:36.000 --> 01:05:39.000
of training and development of employees,

01:05:39.000 --> 01:05:42.000
the employees themselves clearly understand

01:05:42.000 --> 01:05:45.000
what competence is necessary for their career growth.

01:05:45.000 --> 01:05:48.000
They understand what they need to do

01:05:48.000 --> 01:05:51.000
to make their work evaluated positively.

01:05:51.000 --> 01:05:54.000
The employees have a clear idea

01:05:54.000 --> 01:05:57.000
of what their employees were trained for.

01:05:57.000 --> 01:06:00.000
They clearly understand

01:06:00.000 --> 01:06:03.000
what they can demand from their employees.

01:06:03.000 --> 01:06:06.000
The staff receives a good tool

01:06:06.000 --> 01:06:09.000
to evaluate the effectiveness of the investments

01:06:09.000 --> 01:06:12.000
that are invested in training.

01:06:12.000 --> 01:06:15.000
Let's talk about the use of competence

01:06:15.000 --> 01:06:18.000
in the selection of staff.

01:06:18.000 --> 01:06:21.000
We can evaluate the competence

01:06:21.000 --> 01:06:24.000
of a certain employee in 40 minutes,

01:06:24.000 --> 01:06:27.000
an hour, or an hour and a half.

01:06:27.000 --> 01:06:30.000
We have a limited time.

01:06:30.000 --> 01:06:33.000
We didn't know anything about the employee before.

01:06:33.000 --> 01:06:36.000
There is no history of our relations.

01:06:36.000 --> 01:06:39.000
The evaluation should be as accurate as possible.

01:06:39.000 --> 01:06:42.000
We should make every effort

01:06:42.000 --> 01:06:45.000
not to make a mistake.

01:06:45.000 --> 01:06:48.000
The most important thing

01:06:48.000 --> 01:06:51.000
is the direct costs and costs

01:06:51.000 --> 01:06:54.000
that our company is incurring.

01:06:54.000 --> 01:06:57.000
The selection of employees is the most accurate

01:06:57.000 --> 01:07:00.000
if we evaluate them by competence.

01:07:00.000 --> 01:07:03.000
There are two main methods

01:07:03.000 --> 01:07:06.000
that we use.

01:07:06.000 --> 01:07:09.000
The first is the interview by competence.

01:07:09.000 --> 01:07:12.000
The second is the evaluation centers.

01:07:12.000 --> 01:07:15.000
The advantage of the interview by competence

01:07:15.000 --> 01:07:18.000
is that our questions will be based

01:07:18.000 --> 01:07:21.000
on the analysis of the work

01:07:21.000 --> 01:07:24.000
and will be aimed at the development of the skills

01:07:24.000 --> 01:07:27.000
that are required for the work

01:07:27.000 --> 01:07:30.000
that our candidate is applying for.

01:07:30.000 --> 01:07:33.000
The next advantage is that the information

01:07:33.000 --> 01:07:36.000
received during the interview

01:07:36.000 --> 01:07:39.000
will be easier to structure

01:07:39.000 --> 01:07:42.000
and we will easily assign the level of development

01:07:42.000 --> 01:07:45.000
that the employee demonstrates,

01:07:45.000 --> 01:07:48.000
the information that we will gather

01:07:48.000 --> 01:07:51.000
during the interview,

01:07:51.000 --> 01:07:54.000
and the skills that are required for the job.

01:07:54.000 --> 01:07:57.000
Unfortunately, there are disadvantages.

01:07:57.000 --> 01:08:00.000
The first one is the long duration of the interview.

01:08:00.000 --> 01:08:03.000
In this case, it is important to use

01:08:03.000 --> 01:08:06.000
the tool that we talked about today,

01:08:06.000 --> 01:08:09.000
which is the tool of a pair comparison.

01:08:09.000 --> 01:08:12.000
Before preparing for the interview,

01:08:12.000 --> 01:08:15.000
we will determine the critical competencies

01:08:15.000 --> 01:08:18.000
together with the manager.

01:08:18.000 --> 01:08:21.000
What is the priority?

01:08:21.000 --> 01:08:24.000
What competencies should be there?

01:08:24.000 --> 01:08:27.000
In the absence of these competencies,

01:08:27.000 --> 01:08:30.000
we can close our eyes and understand

01:08:30.000 --> 01:08:33.000
that we are simply training this person.

01:08:33.000 --> 01:08:36.000
The manager says that he does not need

01:08:36.000 --> 01:08:39.000
to know the product,

01:08:39.000 --> 01:08:42.000
he just needs to sell it well.

01:08:42.000 --> 01:08:45.000
This competence is more important.

01:08:45.000 --> 01:08:48.000
The other says that he needs to know the product

01:08:48.000 --> 01:08:51.000
because it is a specific product,

01:08:51.000 --> 01:08:54.000
and he will learn to sell it.

01:08:54.000 --> 01:08:57.000
Different situations, different managers,

01:08:57.000 --> 01:09:00.000
and in some similar competencies,

01:09:00.000 --> 01:09:03.000
the two cases will be completely different.

01:09:03.000 --> 01:09:06.000
We talked about the matrix of assessment,

01:09:06.000 --> 01:09:09.000
the matrix of developing actions.

01:09:09.000 --> 01:09:12.000
We also need to have a matrix of questions,

01:09:12.000 --> 01:09:15.000
which we will use to identify

01:09:15.000 --> 01:09:18.000
the competencies that we need.

01:09:18.000 --> 01:09:21.000
The difficulty is that the candidate

01:09:21.000 --> 01:09:24.000
can exaggerate a little.

01:09:24.000 --> 01:09:27.000
Perhaps he will not tell what he did himself,

01:09:27.000 --> 01:09:30.000
but he will show how someone did it,

01:09:30.000 --> 01:09:33.000
as if it were his own project.

01:09:33.000 --> 01:09:36.000
Therefore, we must initially prepare,

01:09:36.000 --> 01:09:39.000
come up with those questions,

01:09:39.000 --> 01:09:42.000
formulate those small tasks,

01:09:42.000 --> 01:09:45.000
and the answers to which will allow us to determine

01:09:45.000 --> 01:09:48.000
whether the candidate is talking about what he knows,

01:09:48.000 --> 01:09:51.000
or he is trying to improvise,

01:09:51.000 --> 01:09:54.000
because he has never done this before.

01:09:54.000 --> 01:09:57.000
We can formulate questions aimed at identifying

01:09:57.000 --> 01:10:00.000
professional competencies.

01:10:00.000 --> 01:10:03.000
For example, we will ask the sales manager

01:10:03.000 --> 01:10:06.000
to give as many solutions as possible

01:10:06.000 --> 01:10:09.000
for the situation when the client requires a discount

01:10:09.000 --> 01:10:12.000
that he cannot give.

01:10:12.000 --> 01:10:15.000
Regardless of the product,

01:10:15.000 --> 01:10:18.000
regardless of the specificity of the company's activities,

01:10:18.000 --> 01:10:21.000
either a person knows how to do it,

01:10:21.000 --> 01:10:24.000
or he has never worked before,

01:10:24.000 --> 01:10:27.000
and his boss has always solved

01:10:27.000 --> 01:10:30.000
such difficult situations with the client.

01:10:30.000 --> 01:10:33.000
It is more difficult to talk about management competencies

01:10:33.000 --> 01:10:36.000
and corporate competencies.

01:10:36.000 --> 01:10:39.000
That is why it is necessary to ask situational questions,

01:10:39.000 --> 01:10:42.000
to offer different situations,

01:10:42.000 --> 01:10:45.000
to reveal how a person would behave in this situation,

01:10:45.000 --> 01:10:48.000
and how he behaved when these situations happened

01:10:48.000 --> 01:10:51.000
during his previous work.

01:10:51.000 --> 01:10:54.000
Thus, by listening to the answers of the candidate during the interview,

01:10:54.000 --> 01:10:57.000
we get a set of positive and negative indicators

01:10:57.000 --> 01:11:00.000
applicable to the competencies

01:11:00.000 --> 01:11:03.000
that we analyze.

01:11:03.000 --> 01:11:06.000
This will allow us to analyze

01:11:06.000 --> 01:11:09.000
the notes that we have left

01:11:09.000 --> 01:11:12.000
and make a preliminary conclusion

01:11:12.000 --> 01:11:15.000
about the competencies

01:11:15.000 --> 01:11:18.000
that the candidate has developed.

01:11:18.000 --> 01:11:21.000
For example, by evaluating the competence

01:11:21.000 --> 01:11:24.000
of the orientation to the result,

01:11:24.000 --> 01:11:27.000
we can ask the candidate questions

01:11:27.000 --> 01:11:30.000
about what professional goals he sets for himself for the next year,

01:11:30.000 --> 01:11:33.000
how ambitious these goals are for him,

01:11:33.000 --> 01:11:36.000
what difficulties he can foresee in achieving these goals,

01:11:36.000 --> 01:11:39.000
and what can prevent him from fulfilling his plans.

01:11:39.000 --> 01:11:42.000
Thus, by listening to his answers and reflection,

01:11:42.000 --> 01:11:45.000
we get a set of positive indicators.

01:11:45.000 --> 01:11:48.000
We can say that this person sets goals for himself,

01:11:48.000 --> 01:11:51.000
that he plans his career for the long term.

01:11:51.000 --> 01:11:54.000
These goals may be professional goals,

01:11:54.000 --> 01:11:57.000
or they may be personal goals.

01:11:57.000 --> 01:12:00.000
Or we get a set of negative indicators.

01:12:00.000 --> 01:12:03.000
When we say that we understand that

01:12:03.000 --> 01:12:06.000
it is clear from the examples that

01:12:06.000 --> 01:12:09.000
a person does not have specific goals,

01:12:09.000 --> 01:12:12.000
or that he does not know how to set them,

01:12:12.000 --> 01:12:15.000
setting certain goals for his own desire,

01:12:15.000 --> 01:12:18.000
his own expectations.

01:12:18.000 --> 01:12:21.000
Thus, in the end, we get some information for analysis.

01:12:21.000 --> 01:12:24.000
When we analyze either a list of negative indicators

01:12:24.000 --> 01:12:27.000
or a list of positive indicators,

01:12:27.000 --> 01:12:30.000
we understand and can evaluate

01:12:30.000 --> 01:12:33.000
what level of competence development,

01:12:33.000 --> 01:12:36.000
the level of competence that we analyzed,

01:12:36.000 --> 01:12:39.000
the orientation to the result of this candidate.

01:12:39.000 --> 01:12:42.000
Then we compare it to the position.

01:12:42.000 --> 01:12:45.000
How critical is it?

01:12:45.000 --> 01:12:48.000
How much does a person in this position

01:12:48.000 --> 01:12:51.000
need to be oriented to the result?

01:12:51.000 --> 01:12:54.000
After that, we understand whether this competence

01:12:54.000 --> 01:12:57.000
was named as a priority.

01:12:57.000 --> 01:13:00.000
Thus, we get a tool for comparing

01:13:00.000 --> 01:13:03.000
completely different candidates.

01:13:07.000 --> 01:13:10.000
Colleagues, to conclude the topic of the application

01:13:10.000 --> 01:13:13.000
of competence models, I will repeat once again

01:13:13.000 --> 01:13:16.000
that, of course, the most profitable are those companies

01:13:16.000 --> 01:13:19.000
where the competence model is the core

01:13:19.000 --> 01:13:22.000
in the system of staff management

01:13:22.000 --> 01:13:25.000
and all functions are tied, integrated

01:13:25.000 --> 01:13:28.000
between them. Thus, the company

01:13:28.000 --> 01:13:31.000
has the opportunity to become more flexible,

01:13:31.000 --> 01:13:34.000
more mobile and better respond to changes

01:13:34.000 --> 01:13:37.000
because, once again, if we re-examine

01:13:37.000 --> 01:13:40.000
the competence after some time,

01:13:40.000 --> 01:13:43.000
we guarantee that all our HR policies

01:13:43.000 --> 01:13:46.000
will be adapted to the changes

01:13:46.000 --> 01:13:49.000
that occur if the competence

01:13:49.000 --> 01:13:52.000
is a key tool.

01:13:52.000 --> 01:13:55.000
Very often we hear that

01:13:55.000 --> 01:13:58.000
there is a competence, but it does not work.

01:13:58.000 --> 01:14:01.000
When you start to think why it does not work,

01:14:01.000 --> 01:14:04.000
the reasons are, most likely,

01:14:04.000 --> 01:14:07.000
the resistance of the management

01:14:07.000 --> 01:14:10.000
and the fact that employees

01:14:10.000 --> 01:14:13.000
find reasons to ignore the competence.

01:14:13.000 --> 01:14:16.000
Why does it happen?

01:14:16.000 --> 01:14:19.000
There may be a number of reasons

01:14:19.000 --> 01:14:22.000
why the competence does not work.

01:14:22.000 --> 01:14:25.000
Let's think about it.

01:14:25.000 --> 01:14:28.000
The first reason is the unreasonable

01:14:28.000 --> 01:14:31.000
reasons for their development and implementation.

01:14:31.000 --> 01:14:34.000
When the company developed the competence

01:14:34.000 --> 01:14:37.000
not because it is necessary,

01:14:37.000 --> 01:14:40.000
but because it is the future tool of staff management.

01:14:40.000 --> 01:14:43.000
Maybe because everyone does it.

01:14:43.000 --> 01:14:46.000
I heard at the conference that

01:14:46.000 --> 01:14:49.000
the competing company has the competence.

01:14:49.000 --> 01:14:52.000
Why not make it ourselves?

01:14:52.000 --> 01:14:55.000
They have the competence.

01:14:55.000 --> 01:14:58.000
It is clear that there are no reasons.

01:15:02.000 --> 01:15:05.000
The second reason is that

01:15:05.000 --> 01:15:08.000
some mistakes were made during the development.

01:15:08.000 --> 01:15:11.000
Maybe the model is too complex?

01:15:11.000 --> 01:15:14.000
Maybe we tried to describe

01:15:14.000 --> 01:15:17.000
all the standards of behavior

01:15:17.000 --> 01:15:20.000
and we got 20 competencies?

01:15:20.000 --> 01:15:23.000
Maybe it is too simple?

01:15:24.000 --> 01:15:27.000
There are only 4 of them

01:15:27.000 --> 01:15:30.000
and employees do not understand

01:15:30.000 --> 01:15:33.000
how their competence affects their work.

01:15:33.000 --> 01:15:36.000
There is a competence. What is it?

01:15:36.000 --> 01:15:39.000
I say, colleagues,

